
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lastlog` baraye didan akharin zamane vorood (login) karbaran be system estefade mishavad. Agar karbari hich vaght vorood nakarde bashad, etela'ati namayesh dade nemishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `lastlog` --> 👤 Namayesh akharin vorood baraye hameye karbaran.
    🔹 `lastlog -u [username]` --> 🎯 Namayesh akharin vorood baraye karbar khas.
    🔹 `lastlog -t [rooz]` --> 📅 Namayesh akharin vorood baraye karbarani ke dar [rooz]-haye gozashte vorood kardeand.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lastlog

    🔹 Namayesh akharin vorood baraye hameye karbaran.

    $ lastlog -u ali

    🔹 Namayesh akharin vorood baraye karbar "ali".

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lastlog -t 7

    🔹 Namayesh akharin vorood baraye karbarani ke dar 7 rooze gozashte vorood kardeand. Karbarani ke bishtar az 7 rooz pish vorood kardeand, namayesh dade nemishavand.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lastlog` command is used to examine the most recent login times of all users or a specific user on the system. If a user has never logged in, no information is displayed for that user.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `lastlog` --> 👤 Display the last login time for all users.
    🔹 `lastlog -u [username]` --> 🎯 Display the last login time for a specific user.
    🔹 `lastlog -t [days]` --> 📅 Display the last login time for users who logged in within the last [days].

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lastlog

    🔹 Display the last login time for all users.

    $ lastlog -u alice

    🔹 Display the last login time for the user "alice".

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lastlog -t 30

    🔹 Display the last login time for users who logged in within the last 30 days. Users who logged in more than 30 days ago will not be displayed.
